where formula_17 are non-random but unobservable parameters, formula_18 are non-random and observable (called the &quot;explanatory variables&quot;), formula_19 are random, and so formula_20 are random. The random variables formula_19 are called the &quot;disturbance&quot;, &quot;noise&quot; or simply &quot;error&quot; (will be contrasted with &quot;residual&quot; later in the article; see errors and residuals in statistics). Note that to include a constant in the model above, one can choose to introduce the constant as a variable formula_22 with a newly introduced last column of X being unity i.e., formula_23 for all formula_24. Note that though formula_25 as sample responses, are observable, the following statements and arguments including assumptions, proofs and the others assume under the only condition of knowing formula_26 but not formula_27

The Gauss–Markov assumptions concern the set of error random variables, formula_19:

*They have mean zero: formula_29
*They are homoscedastic, that is all have the same finite variance: formula_30 for all formula_31 and
*Distinct error terms are uncorrelated: formula_32

A linear estimator of formula_33 is a linear combination

:formula_34

in which the coefficients formula_35 are not allowed to depend on the underlying coefficients formula_17, since those are not observable, but are allowed to depend on the values formula_37, since these data are observable. (The dependence of the coefficients on each formula_18 is typically nonlinear; the estimator is linear in each formula_39 and hence in each random formula_40 which is why this is &quot;linear&quot; regression.) The estimator is said to be unbiased if and only if

:formula_41

regardless of the values of formula_37. Now, let formula_43 be some linear combination of the coefficients. Then the mean squared error of the corresponding estimation is

:formula_44

in other words, it is the expectation of the square of the weighted sum (across parameters) of the differences between the estimators and the corresponding parameters to be estimated. (Since we are considering the case in which all the parameter estimates are unbiased, this mean squared error is the same as the variance of the linear combination.) The best linear unbiased estimator (BLUE) of the vector formula_45 of parameters formula_46 is one with the smallest mean squared error for every vector formula_47 of linear combination parameters. This is equivalent to the condition that

:formula_48

is a positive semi-definite matrix for every other linear unbiased estimator formula_49.

The ordinary least squares estimator (OLS) is the function

:formula_50

of formula_51 and formula_3 (where formula_53 denotes the transpose of formula_10) that minimizes the sum of squares of residuals (misprediction amounts):

:formula_55

The theorem now states that the OLS estimator is a best linear unbiased estimator (BLUE). 

The main idea of the proof is that the least-squares estimator is uncorrelated with every linear unbiased estimator of zero, i.e., with every linear combination formula_56 whose coefficients do not depend upon the unobservable formula_45 but whose expected value is always zero.

